Question - What is a Method in C#?
Answer -
â€¢ A method in C# is a block of code that performs a specific task.
â€¢ It may/may not take parameters 
â€¢ It may or may not return a value.
â€¢ Methods are also called functions in C#.
â€¢ A method is used to perform specific operations.
â€¢ Methods are declared inside a class.
â€¢ Methods can be reused â€” define once and call multiple times.
â€¢ Every C# program has at least one method called Main().
â€¢ Methods help organize code, improve reusability, and simplify debugging.
â€¢ Every C# program has a Main method as the entry point 

Syntax of a Method:
AccessSpecifier  ReturnType   MethodName(Parameter List)
{
   Method Body
}

Examples:

1) Method with no parameters and no return value:
   public void Greet()
   {
       Console.WriteLine("Hello!");
   }

2) Method with parameters and a return value:
   private int Add(int a, int b)
   {
       return a + b;
   }

Method Naming Rules:
â€¢ Cannot - C# keywords.
â€¢ Cannot contain spaces/start with a digit.
â€¢ It cannot have spaces.
â€¢ It Can begin with a letter, underscore (_) or the @ symbol.
â€¢ It should be meaningful and describe the purpose of the method.
  Examples: Add(), sum_Add(), @Add()

Complete Example:

using System;
namespace Method
{
    class Program
    {
        static void MyMethod()
        {
            Console.WriteLine("My name is ALOK KUMAR PANDEY.");
        }

        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            MyMethod();
        }
    }
}
Output:
My name is ALOK KUMAR PANDEY.


